segments.text: Um, it's March the 14th, 1984.
My name is Bree Dodd, and I'm in the office of Walter Johnson.
Jackson.
Jackson.
Always do that.
And we're here to discuss the history of planning in Galveston.
The current history of planning in Galveston.
Well, current history.
I don't know very little.
I'm not sure Galveston did a very good job of planning in some cases, especially in the last 20 years.
But, uh, uh,
Gal, I just can't speak to the historical development of planning.
I do know that from in the earlier, the formation years of Galveston, there certainly had to be a lot of planning, had to be a lot of studies and ways to

create and make a city on a barrier island functional and they were successful for quite a while and especially following such things as the 1900 storm where 6,000 lives were lost and the whole city had to be the grade level raised and the
the development of city government, which came about in Galveston, as we know, or the manager council form of government.

Today, Galveston seems to be doing a fairly good job of trying to study some of its needs, but it still appears that most of it is reaction to things that are happening instead of long-range planning or, you know, not...
I think our problem is, lately, we may have...
failed to plan instead of planning to fail, but we failed anyway, especially in the 60s and 70s.
But it's coming back now where folks are really taking a look at long-range plans as well as short-range plans.
We have problems of water down here.
Where are we going to get our water supply?
That's been served well with contracts.
Bind water from Houston for the next 30 years.
lousy job of planning how we're going to keep our streets and sewers and upgrade our city services in conjunction with the tax limitations that have been imposed by the voters of Galveston.
And we're really facing a strong dilemma, a big dilemma in that area right now.
And I don't know what's going to happen, but we better get some good planners that can figure out something to do and sell it to the people.
I think planning is

planning certainly has to be addressed in the future, and they're looking at it to some extent now, but as it has to do with being on a barrier island and the shift of the vegetation lines, development up and down the seawall, or all development on this island, and what problems we do face.
And that probably has not been adequately done either, but
You know, it's some of that's going to have to be done and will in the future.
Let's look at your list here.
See what else we do.
I don't know.
There is a comprehensive plan.
They have a lot of that systematic stuff.
They'll have to tell you at City Hall about that.
Transportation is a tremendous problem here.
We sure need to plan better for evacuation from hurricanes and storms.
We only have
one real good exit off this island, which is the Galveston Causeway and Interstate 45 and Hurricane Allen showed us what a mess that is when you're trying to evacuate.
So that's certainly a problem.
How the influences affect affected planning in our community?
Well, I think probably all these categories have had some effect politically.
Galveston is a very political town and things seem to wind up in issues and fighting things out on the ballot instead of doing a good job of studying the problems and working them out.
Our geographic location, as we've talked about, certainly has a big role in that.
I really don't think religious or ethnic have affected us too much except to the fact that
We have probably had a lack of planning and good management in the city because we lack a strong middle class in this community.
We have a majority of lower income people and quite a few higher income people, but most of the middle class people tend to migrate towards the mainland, Dickinson, Clear Lake area.
Even though they work here, they drive home at night.

across the causeway and really have not gotten into the political arena and pressed for some of the changes that I think fast growing suburban areas tend to do because it's probably geographic and it's sociological and it's probably educational.
We tend to have a high college professor
tight mentality coming from the medical branch, which would tend to be more environmentalist and tend to lean to one direction.
And we have a strong blue collar background here, but just
which they tend to accept things as they are and don't tend to really care about changing too much or studying it.
We have studied problems.

As long as the federal government gives us money to study problems, we'll find 10 or 15 people that want to go out and get some of that money to study it, but those studies tend to wind up on the shelf somewhere and never really get implemented.

some of the things that I think we really need to be planning for in the future as far as long range and the development of Galveston certainly is transportation as we were talking about not only access into the island but once people get here how are we going to move them we are finally in an upward mobility type situation as far as population and we're gonna we've got
new people moving here, as well as a tremendous increase in tourist and visitor traffic, and that's going to require some tremendous planning in how to handle this in future years.
As I mentioned, the water problem seems to be planned pretty well.
City utilities, city services certainly is a weak area, and you've got to plan for the dollars as well as plan where you're going to put things and how you're going to do it.
That seems to be a weak area we need to get into.
We've touched on the economic through all of this.
Military, we're not
significantly impact by the military.

However, we are significantly impact by governmental agencies and governmental services, which have created a lower tax base because we have so much tax exempt property that are do not go into the do not generate taxes.
And it's it's it's put us in a money crunch from that angle as well as the tax limitations.
I promise you all these things in here have

can be addressed for galveston though starting with the spanish era all the way up it'd be interesting to see what you come up with because especially from the civil war the republic of texas own and even the mexican era but all of those really it would be fun to go back and see how it how it affects i just don't know but uh... uh... i imagine a lot of the things that started in in planning of cities especially in the state of texas probably started right here in galveston if you can go find
where to get it out, because nearly everything that happened started in Galveston.
So if you can get some good research material or get hold of somebody that knows, I'll tell you a good interview would be Bob Nesbitt.
He's a historian here.
Do you know Bob?
No.
Robert Nesbitt?
Let me write his name down, because Bob probably could tell you all of this.
He worked with Ray Miller.
Do you know who Ray Miller is?
I don't know.
The Eyes of Texas and does, you know, all of that.
But he...

He would be a tremendous, and he's a nice fella, and he would take the time to really sit down and give you a good chronological development and everything, and he would know it and have support material for it too.
Oh, well, fantastic.
Let me see if I can get his phone number for you.
Oh, that would be even better.
I know the problems.
I just don't know what's always being done.
We do things like planning for, you know, working with the school, working with the city on immediate things like bond issues and streets and roads and the water problems.
But the overall part, which I think really will tie into this later, and you'll see why we have such a problem now, somebody like Bob could really do you a good job.
Why don't we take this from a different angle, how the planning has affected the businesses in Galveston?
Well, the lack of planning probably has had a tremendous effect on them simply from what to do with downtown, you know.
Downtowns have had trouble before and they've got central business districts all over tend to be having troubles and
The lack of doing good planning and finding out the pitfalls and having a few failures, such as our Central Mall area and everything, it has had some effect on us.

On the other hand, you can say that planning from the development of historical restoration and from those ends are having tremendous gains for us and probably are going to be the lifeblood of the redevelopment of the Central Business District.
The ability to come out with
some ordinances and some whatever from city hall that allows for zoning.
It allows for the development or the restoration of the historical areas, the strand area, and pretty much the city as a whole since we have so much historical significance.
One other question, Dallas.
I think we've touched on most of it.
I think so, too.
Like I say, I'm just not familiar enough to really get into the nuts and bolts of it.
But boy, Bob, Bob.
And tell him who you are, because he'd love to help you.
He is a super nice guy, and he would be a super source.
And what he doesn't know, he certainly would know where to refer you.
I know to refer you to City Hall or people like that, or people that may give you an opinion one way or the other, but really good factual information.
other than Rosenberg Library or somebody like Bob that knows the city.
Well, I think you've given me some very good information.
Well, hopefully it'll help you some.
Oh, yes, I'm sure it will.
Thank you very much.
Thank you.
You driving back and forth, or y'all?
My name is Bree Dodd, and I'm in the office of Roger Hedrick.
And it's March the 17th, 16th, 1984.
Okay, and we're here to discuss the history of planning in Galveston.
Okay, question one.
When was the first legislative authorization of a comprehensive plan in Galveston?
As far as I know, the first authorization came about when the current city charter was adopted in 1961.
A major part of that city charter revolved around the new form of government.
You may recall that back in 1900, after the 1900 hurricane or major storm,
the city of Galveston invented a new form of government called the commission form of government.
That form of government was in effect until 1961, when by a vote of the people, the city charter was adopted and the city manager form of government was instituted.
That was also the time where there was something in the city charter called Article 10, which dealt specifically with planning.
That's when
A planning commission was formed prior to that time.
As I understand it, it was primarily a zoning commission.

The powers and duties of the planning commission were set out, including recommendations to city council, the annual submission of a capital improvements budget, the final authority for disapproval and approval of subdivision flats,
and, of course, the authority to prepare a master plan or a comprehensive plan.
Another feature of this charter, as long as I'm on it, was that it set forth the creation of a position called the director of planning.

So this is called for in the charter itself that the director is appointed by the city manager, and he's got to have certain, well, let me quote, who shall be qualified by special training and experience in the field of city planning.
And then it goes into what are some of the components of the master plan or comprehensive plan and what the legal effect of the master plan.
So it was really first authorized, as far as I know, in 1961.
As far as when a plan was approved, components
components of a comprehensive plan were passed.
Starting in 1963, a report on population land use thoroughfares and transportation was prepared by urban planning and area development consultants.
That was June of 63.
Also in 63, a public utilities plan was prepared by Forrest and Cotton.
In July of 65, the Galveston Central Business District plan was reported, pardon me, report was prepared by Marvin Springer and Associates.
Also in 1965, a housing community facilities
plan report was prepared by Marvin Springer.
In 65, also, people and land use thoroughfares business district beachfront housing and community facilities plan was again done by Marvin Springer and Associates.
Then we jump to some period in time when the plan, I guess you would say, was largely modified or a new plan appeared
in 1973 by Marvin Springer and Associates to be adopted by council then the following year in 74.
Now I would like to point out that because the city of Galveston only basically went to the end of the seawall, the western part of Galveston was not included in that plan.
So to this day we don't really have a comprehensive plan in existence
for the west end of Galveston Island.
Also, at least to how I define a plan, many things were missing besides simply the rest of the island.
There weren't really a lot of clear-cut goals and objectives and policies.
A year later, let's see if it was a year later,

pardon me, it was even in 1976, which might have been a year or two later, that an independent, really non-official city-sponsored group got together and did a goals for Galveston plan, which really kind of, I guess, complemented the comprehensive plan, although normally goals come before a comprehensive plan.
So things were done a little bit differently then.
And
Since that time, well, we do not have any systematic periodic review of our city's comprehensive plan.
However, the planning staff sees the island largely as two different areas.
The older, more urbanized part of the island, which is that 10 miles behind the seawall, and those remaining 20 miles of the island
which are largely resort-oriented or second homes, that there is a large amount of land available that can be planned for on the west end of the island.
But as far as the east end, that is mainly it doesn't have growth, but it has redevelopment potential.
And so our basic process to bring about land use planning to Galveston has kind of two concepts.
The first one is we got started in going through the older part of Galveston on a neighborhood by neighborhood basis.
And to date, we have two neighborhood plans which have been adopted by the Planning Commission and City Council.
Which neighborhoods are those?
That's the East End and Old Central.
We have two neighborhood plans in process which are nearly completed.
And those...
Those are Carver Park and the Kempner Park neighborhoods.
Beyond those four, there still are a good six to eight plans which no funding has been identified yet or a way of undertaking those plans.
Although I would like to point out that in 1982, the city council
did officially recognize geographically about a dozen neighborhoods within the city.
And we established a priority system for going through the older parts of the city and doing it on a neighborhood by neighborhood planning basis.
But again, we have not identified funds at this time to continue that program beyond this year.
We had funded those plans through community development block grant program, but those funds have been diminishing and council's priorities have been changing.
Lastly, I would comment that we have a proposal which has gained acceptance by the Planning Commission and City Council to do a comprehensive plan this year for Galveston Island.
I can give you a copy of that if you'd like that.
Oh, fantastic.
Can I bring it back for you right now so I don't forget about it?
Catherine.
Okay.
Would you also bring another copy of one of these things, please?
You want a copy of that?
Yeah.
They're back there with Catherine.
Okay.
This is a staff proposal, which basically proposes to do a comprehensive plan for the entire city of Galveston, which would be all of Galveston Island and all of Pelican Island.
Galveston really is two islands.
And there's basically two land holes in Galveston.
It excludes an area called Pirates Beach, Pirates Cove, which is a separate municipal utilities district, which is unincorporated.
It's a part of the county.
And also Bermuda Beach, which is a separate city unto itself on West Galveston.
Yeah, I think we've answered.
Two, three, let's see, four.
Yeah, I would say we do an awful lot of incremental planning.
But again, with those two concepts of trying to do the old parts of town through neighborhood planning and
This proposal that the staff has put together would basically rely on existing plans in the older part of town and try and weave them together.
In the western part of Galveston, it really is very much different.
It's very ecologically sensitive, so we anticipate using what we call coastal zone management principles, which are more applicable to barrier islands in that particular part of town.
Boy, when was the first one?
Isn't that basically from Clark's book on coastal zone management and finding what tidal areas are, et cetera?
I would say I have read Clark's book, and I would say that, I guess, has been kind of the Bible, so to speak.
And although we have reviewed other barrier island plans and incorporated the ideas there, notably Sanibel Island off of Florida.
Have they been very successful and that's why you're basing some of your principles on that plan?
I don't know how successful the plan is, but the techniques of planning appear to be very successful and appear to be state of the art.
And certainly because of the individuals involved in the preparation of that plan, I have a great deal of confidence in the methodology.
That was Wallace McHarg, Robertson Todd out of Philadelphia.
The Conservation Fund was involved in addition to, I think, a lot of local participation.
When was the first zoning ordinance?
I would have to talk to the city...
Can I have one of the ladies call down?
Sir.
Okay.
I'll call down myself.
Oh.
By the way, I'd like the Xerox to cover so I have the bibliographical information.
Okay.
This is Roger.
Can you tell me when the first zoning ordinance was adopted by, I guess, a city council?
1937 was the very first one.
Very fine.
Thank you.
Bye-bye.
So this is another city where zoning came before comprehensive planning.
Well, yeah, and of course, you know, all that does is follow the federal state way of doing things, too, because, you know, the federal legislation, you know,
And of course, in the state of Texas, while we have zoning enabling legislation, we do not have planning enabling legislation yet.

Although, I've recently received a proposal from Richard Lilly, who is basically a head of legislative affairs for Texas chapter APA, and he's proposed a two-part program for drafting new legislation this year.
The first part was to basically survey planning directors and executive board members on what the issues were that should be studied and recommendations then brought to the Texas Municipal League.
And secondly, the drafting of enabling legislation on comprehensive planning.
So I guess that's really a side issue, but it fits in.
Okay, number seven is what procedures do we have for implementing community plans?
Okay, let me see if I can remember my, the state legislation.
Well, the tools available for all cities in Texas,
The tools available for Galveston also to carry out the plan involve grants of authority from the state and consist of four powers.
Regulatory, eminent domain, taxation, and the spending power.
As far as planning and the planning department, we've only been involved in two of those powers.
The first one, of course, is regulatory.
We're involved on a regular basis through zoning and subdivision regulations.
And then the spending power, we are involved through our capital improvements plan and program.
So that is that.
What CIP are you currently working on?
Well, actually, I think our CIP has been rather successful as of late.
Of course, I too say success of a plan is only
if a plan is implemented.

And in this case, council named something they called the Executive Bond Committee, which comprised of members largely of the Planning Commission, in addition to a bond expert and a member of the Chamber of Commerce, and put together a bond proposal.
And city council is now on record of taking this to the voters on August of this year, August of 84.
What is very unusual, I guess, about this is that the last time, there's two things, really.
Galveston hasn't had a bond issue that I'm aware of, a general bond issue, since about 1964 was the last time.
So it's been about 20 years or two decades.
The other major issue involved, which is to why I think...

this is a particularly unique planning program, is that there occurred a charter amendment which limited to increases in city budget to no more than 7% a year, which on the current situation, there is no way to pass a bond issue and then pay the bonds back through general revenue sources.

So on this same August election date, they will also have to place on there, if they want to proceed in a timely fashion, an amendment to the charter to take the budget limitations of general obligation bonds from under this budget lid, which was placed there by the taxpayers.
So this is a two-fold situation.
When did the city first establish a planning department?
Let me call the city secretary.
She's been around for quite a while.
Linda, this is Roger.
I've got a tough question for you.
When did the city establish the first planning department?
You say why?
You don't know?
Okay, can you bounce that off of Patsy and see if she knows?
Thank you.
Concerning professional planners on the staff, we have two planners in addition to myself, the director, who are what I would consider professional planners.
We're anticipating hiring one more planner.
So it would be a staff of three planners and one director.
We also have a compliance officer, zoning compliance officer, who is not trained in planning, but obviously he is enforcing the zoning codes.
While we're waiting, I see that you have a background in landscape architecture.
I think that's sort of interesting.
Because I'm a landscape architect.
Oh, is that right?
Well, I'm highly biased, but I certainly think that's probably one of the better backgrounds for physical city planning.
Well, I agree.
And you'll note I don't have a degree in city planning.
Public administration.
Right, right.
Which to me, planning kind of wedges itself in between public administration and landscape is a little more nitty gritty site planning type of stuff.
And public administration tends to be even broader.
Yes.
And perhaps even more policy oriented.
Certainly.
Yeah, this is Roger.
Can you tell me when the first planning department was formed?
OK. OK. OK, prior to that date, then, the Planning Commission just did all the work.
And they only did zoning up until that point.
OK, but you must have had zoning cases then.
And only, OK, and you didn't have a staff for that commission, in other words.
Very good.
OK. OK.
There was a zoning commission until 1961.
Then it became a?
Oh.
OK. Was it since 37 that there was a separate zoning and planning?
OK. See, at one time, there were two separate commissions, which is not unusual.
There's a zoning commission and a planning commission.
And Patsy's trying to recall the city secretary exactly when all this came about.
But there was not a planning staff per se until 1961 when the city charter was adopted.
Was there a director at that time?
Or did they just hire out consultants?
She said planning department.
Because I got the impression that Marvin Springer and Associates was a consultant.
Well, yeah.
But that would probably be likely.
It's easy to rationalize that if they hired one guy, and he's it.
Of course.
OK. Let me just repeat this for someone else's benefit.
August the 5th, 1937, zoning regulations were established.
The zoning commission was established in a later year or two.
Okay.
Okay.
Was there a separate planning commission?
Oh, okay.
Okay, so a separate planning commission was formed in 61.
In 1973, they combined the planning and the zoning commission into one, and that's the way it's been ever since.
Very good.
Thanks for your help.
That is interesting.
I hope you send me a copy of what you're doing, because I'm not going to remember all this stuff.
I can send you a transcript and then the final article.
OK, that would be great.
Number 10 is really easier to show you a picture than it is to describe it.
Would you like a copy of this?
Yes.
That would be good.
OK. Rather than describe it, can I just refer to it?
Sure.
OK.
Question number 10 refers to the organizational structure and its relationship with the legislative body and citizens groups.
Rather than try and totally describe it, I'll just say that we have a city manager form of government.
The planning department supports four different boards, those boards being

the City Planning Commission, the Zoning Board of Adjustment, the Historical District Board, and a new committee which was just formed called, if we haven't met yet, the Hazardous Materials Technical Advisory, or pardon me, Ad Hoc Advisory Committee.
From time to time, City Council has also formed various committees which we have supported.
There has been a Record Service Code Committee,
because we also administer the record code for the city.
There's a hazardous materials committee, which is different than the one I just named because we prepared a hazardous materials transportation and storage plan for the city.
And also the executive bond committee is another committee which we have supported.
That's pretty much it.
OK, let me get this off of this.
Oh, and the bibliographic.
Oh, okay.
You just want the front page?
Yes.
Oh, boy.
Founding of a city.
Was it planned?
How did this event play a role in your city's planning history?
Okay.
I can't think of the guy's name right now, but when I get that book back...
The town was laid out by a gentleman in a grid fashion.
And so that definitely played a major role.
Frontier functions.
Well, Galveston Island was originally inhabited, as I understand it, during the cooler months, at least, by Indians.
It was also provided a harbor.
It's a natural deep harbor for pirates.
Probably, the railroad did not have
Well, it had an impact, but obviously the port facilities played a much larger role as far as transportation goes.
There was an air base here that goes back to World War II.
I'm a little foggy on some of the history of all that.
But you still see remnants of that when you go down to the hotel under construction and you see the bunker, which is the new hotel that's being built around.
You go down and see the San Luis Pass, oh, somewhere on the 40-hundred block on Seawall Boulevard.
That's a gun emplacement, you know, thick concrete kind of thing.
Urban renewal was totally rejected by the citizens of Galveston.
It's something they did not want.
Luckily.
Concerning the freeways, obviously, Galveston's connection to the mainland is pretty tenuous.
We have one primary access point, and that's Interstate 45 across the causeway.
a ferry boat, which can take you to Port Bolivar and on up to Beaumont and other places east on to Louisiana.
And to the west, there is also a bridge which hooks up to the Freeport and the other chain of islands down to the south and west going on down.
And of course, there is the airport.
And, of course, there is the Houston Ship Channel.
So those are pretty much the modes of transportation, although we are connected by a separate railroad bridge also.

Of course, there is no passenger service at this time, but there has been continual discussion, at least since I've been here, I've been here for four years now, about re-establishing some type of passenger service to the mainland.
The old railroad station
has been part of it has been converted to a railroad museum.
And so that might be the obvious point to depart from again.
Significant public development projects.
Oh, yes.
There was one that is much larger than all the rest combined, and that is the seawall itself, which was the result of the 1900 storm in which 6,000 people were killed.

Work started one or two years after that traumatic event, and today we have a seawall which is some 17 feet in height, made of concrete, with rubble at the base these days because of erosion, and a four to six lane road on top with sidewalks called Seawall Boulevard.
I think I mentioned it's 10 miles in length.
So that was the major public works project.
I think we've talked about the city's chartering changes, and it had a great deal of impact on planning.
They can fire me, and they can reduce my salary, but they can't eliminate the position unless there's a vote of the people.
Consultants definitely have played a role in city planning here, as they often do.
I think in the early years, because of a lack of expertise back in the 60s, city planning was really just starting to come of age with the help of 701 planning funds.
And cities just didn't have the expertise on board.
So I think most of the comprehensive planning direction came from consultants.

I think that's different from today, where you can see it's the staff which has prepared the comprehensive plan proposal, although we do not have the staff on board in sufficient quantity to carry it out, as is indicated there.
And so we propose basically a one-third, two-thirds mix as far as man hours involved.
but where the staff would give guidance to the plan and obviously the planning commission would oversee it and the council would approve a plan eventually.
The current status of planning in the city remains political.
You know, it's up and down.
Although I think it continues to gain support when you can see that planners are here to stay and I think people...
and that they have everyone's interest in mind.
And when you have a staff that manages to stay for a few years and become more a part of the community.
How have the following influences affected planning in your community?
Here's this.
OK.

There have been strong political influence in this community, largely, I think, going back to the turn of the century and when Galveston was kind of what was known at that time as the Wall Street of the Southwest, an extremely wealthy town.
And since that time,
Two, three, or four, maybe slightly more.
